Problems
========
1. Missing error handling  
   • `fetch()` rejects on network errors and `response.json()` rejects on invalid JSON. Both rejections are uncaught.  
   • If the server returns 4xx/5xx, `response.ok` is `false` but the code still tries to parse the body, hiding the real failure.

2. Input is not validated or encoded  
   • `id` is interpolated directly in the URL. A user-supplied value such as `../../admin` or `"; DROP TABLE users;--` could be forwarded to the server unchanged.  
   • If this string is later rendered in the DOM it creates an XSS surface.

3. No timeout / abort logic  
   A slow or hanging request will keep the promise open forever, leading to resource leaks or an unresponsive UI.

4. No authentication / CSRF protection  
   The call does not send credentials or an auth token, and it offers no CSRF protection. (Whether you need them depends on the back-end, but the helper function should make it easy to include them.)

5. No content-type negotiation  
   The caller assumes the server returns JSON. If the server changes (or sends HTML for an error), `response.json()` will throw.

6. Not portable to Node.js  
   In Node ≤18 there is no global `fetch`; the code will fail unless a polyfill (`node-fetch`, undici etc.) is added.

7. Lack of type information / documentation  
   A helper like this should document the expected type of `id` and the shape of the returned object (especially in TypeScript).

How to fix
==========

```js
/**
 * Fetch a user by id.
 * @param {string|number} id - User identifier (will be URI-encoded).
 * @param {object}  [options]
 * @param {AbortSignal} [options.signal] - Optional AbortController signal.
 * @returns {Promise<object>} Parsed JSON user record.
 * @throws {TypeError}           If id is invalid.
 * @throws {NetworkError}        On network failure.
 * @throws {HttpError}           On non-2xx/3xx HTTP status.
 * @throws {SyntaxError}         If response is not valid JSON.
 */
export async function getUser(id, { signal } = {}) {
  // 1. Validate & encode the identifier
  if (id === null || id === undefined ||
      (typeof id !== 'string' && typeof id !== 'number')) {
    throw new TypeError('id must be a string or number');
  }
  const safeId = encodeURIComponent(String(id));

  // 2. Build request options
  const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${safeId}`, {
    method: 'GET',
    headers: { 'Accept': 'application/json' },
    credentials: 'same-origin',  // send cookies if needed
    signal,                      // allow caller to abort
    // Optional: mode: 'same-origin', cache: 'no-store',
  }).catch(err => {
    // Network error (no HTTP status available)
    err.name = 'NetworkError';
    throw err;
  });

  // 3. Reject on HTTP errors
  if (!response.ok) {
    const message = await response.text().catch(() => '');
    const error   = new Error(
      `Request failed: ${response.status} ${response.statusText}` +
      (message ? ` – ${message}` : '')
    );
    error.name   = 'HttpError';
    error.status = response.status;
    error.body   = message;
    throw error;
  }

  // 4. Parse JSON safely
  const data = await response.json();
  // Optional: runtime schema validation goes here
  return data;
}
```

Additional improvements
-----------------------
• Timeout helper:

```js
const controller = new AbortController();
const id = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), 8000); // 8 s timeout
getUser(userId, { signal: controller.signal })
  .finally(() => clearTimeout(id));
```

• Centralize API calls behind an “api client” so you can add automatic retries, refresh expired tokens, etc.

• If you use TypeScript:

```ts
interface User { id: string; name: string; /* … */ }
export async function getUser(id: string | number, opts?): Promise<User> { … }
```

• Ensure the server also validates `id` server-side; never rely solely on client-side sanitization.

By validating inputs, handling every failure path, supporting abort/timeout, and explicitly negotiating JSON, the helper becomes safer, more reliable, and easier to maintain.
